{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_gaston_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583978/1910122501/0963.xml":{"full_text":"He Is 55 Years Old,\nBut Young in Vitality\n\\3\u00bb\nf\nTh* vigor of youth can b# hut on* thing\u2014YTtaTTty. The man who pos\nsesses an abundant vitality never grows old: be will be younger at 60 than\nthe man of SO whose vitality has been sapped, and who has taken no means\nto restore It. The great scientists of today are unanimous on the point\nthat vitality is the true secret of what we call perpetual youth. If I can\nrenew your vitality. I can make you young and keep yon young forever.\nI have found the true supply of manly strength. My Health Belt is a\ngreet natural restorer; you wear It nights while asleep, and thus during\nthe period of your rest, when the vital energy Is the lowest. It pours a\ngreat stream of electro-vitality Into your weakened organs and\nsystem. It never ceases for a single moment; hour after hour the great\nflow of warm, new life and strength passes silently Into your blood, nerves\nand organs; you feel better Immediately, the pains In your back may be\nexpected to disappear In one night; the electro-suspensory attachment is\nfree with each Health Belt for men; It carries the life and strength of the\ncurrent to the weakened parts; a month or two will make a new man of\nyou: courage win return: you will get up mornings healthy, vigorous and\ngood natured with yourself and the world: you will be a permanent member\nof the 'FEELING FINE\" class; your women and men friends will remark\nyour change: you will be a man among men. This Is the exact experience\nof thousands befors you. Hera for Instance, is a letter taken from my\nmail; \"l am a man again, thanks to your wonderful Health Belt. Ess my\ntestimony as you see It. C. L. SNELL. Mlddleport. If. Y.\"\nLet Me Send You This Book FREE\nIt fully describe* my Health Beit and contains\nmuch valuable Information. One part deals with\nvarious ailments common to both men and women.\nThe other part is a prtvate treatise for men only.\nThe complete book sent upon application, free,\nsealed, by mail\nIf In or near this city, take the time to drop in\nmy office that you may see. examine and try ftie\nBelt. No charge for professional advice either at\nray office or by mail. If you oannot call, fill In the\ncoupon and get the free book by return mall. It Is\nbetter than a fortune for any one needing new\nvigor. Hours, 9 to 6; Sundays, 10 to L\nWITH THOSE WHO LABOR\nIN THE LORD\u2019S VINEYARD\nBY D. V. FRANCIS\nNew York, December 34.\u2014(\u201cSpecial.)\u2014The\ncolleges and high schools of the country\nire to be evangelized if the plans of the\nsvangelistic committee of the Methodist\nEpiscopal general conference are carried\nfjut, and they have already been begun.\nThe work is first to be carried on in those\ninstitutions which are under the control\nof the denomination but ultimately other\ndenominations are expected to take up\nthe work and then a concerted move will\nbe made on the undenomination schools\nand colleges.\nThe general outline of the proposed\nwork has three marked features:\n1. Direct evangelistic meetings, in which\nthe claims of Christ on the individual will\noe presented with directness, so that\ngvery student will not only see the obliga\ntion of discipleship, hut see how intel\nligently to begin.\n2. Personal interview work for eight or\nmore hours a day, in which an attempt\nwill be made by the leader of the cam\npaign to talk personally about Christmas\nand His claims to every influential stu\ndent in the institution.\n3. A recruiting campaign for Christian\nworkers. A series of life-work confer\nences are being planned. \u201cThe sacrificial\nlife, the call of Christ,\u201d is to be the dom\ninant note sounded out for all men and\nwomen as future leaders of the church,\nand the distinctive plea made that Christ\nneeds sacrificial men and women in the\nhome. In commerce, in professional life,\nIn civic responsibility, in the pew as well\na.s the pulpit; everywhere Christ calls men\ntr bleed in order to bless. Then will fol\nlow conferences on the gospel ministry,\nhome and foreign missionary work, teach\ning deaconess work, and all other forms\nof life-work service. As a result of this\nrecruiting campaign it is expected that\nhundreds of our best trained men and\nwomen will give themselves to Christ for\nthe work of the church as He shall need\nthem. The meetings planned for next\nmonth are:\nUniversity of Chattanooga, January\n30. February 6, 1911, F. B. Upham,\nSouth Norwalk. Conn.; Clarke univer\nsity, including Gammon Theological\nseminary (Atlanta, Ga.), January 2-3,\nJ. O. Randall, Chicago, 111.; Cornell\ncollege. *arly In February, J. O. Ran\ndall, Chicago: Dakota Wesleyan univer\nsity, January 23-29,1911, George C.\nPeck. New York city; University of\nDenver, January 23-29, 1911, Frost\nGraft; Depauw universlty.January 21-24;\nF. W. Hannan, Brooklyn; Dickinson col\nlege, January 23-29. Allan MacRossie,\nNew York city; Goucher college, De\ncember 6-11, Wallace MacMullen, New\nYork city; Illinois Woman'B college,\nlatter part of January. 1911, Hugh F.\nKmith; Lob Angeles, Cal.; W. F. Stew\nart, Detroit, Mich.; Montpelier semin\nary, January 23-29 G. F. Durgin, Bos\nton; Tilton seminary, January 23-29, A.\nC. McRea, Jersey City, N. J.; Dickin\nson seminary, January 23-29. J. H. Mac\nDonald, Newark. N. J.; Wyoming sem-\ninary, January 23-29, F. \\V. Adams,\nBehenectoday, N. Y.\nAdvices are received from Rome that\nthe consistory to fill the vacancies in\nthe Sacred College of Cardinals will\nnot he held until 1911. Very probably\nIn the first quarter of the new year.\nSo far this year the Holy See has\nnsd to lament the loss of only two\nprinces of the church, the late Cardinal\nKatolli, who^ died in the first week of\n1910; and oh November 24, the death\nof Cardinal Zabaraella occurred. This\ndeath reduces the sacred college to 51\n\u201419 short of the \u201cplenum\" of 70 and\nIS less than the number in it at the\nlast conclave.\nDuring the last pontificate tbe car\ndinals In Curia constituted about half\nthe sacred college\u2014now they are only\n21 and half a dozen of these are pre\nvented by age and Infirmity from tak\ning an active part in the governmeni\nof the church. From the lists of the\n\"Annuaire Ellcesstique\" it will be seen\nthat the chief helpers of Pope Pius X\nare those whose age would imply the\ngreatest activity. The youngest is Car\ndinal Merry del Val, secretary of state.\non whose shoulders falls the greatest\nshare of the difficulties and problems\nof the present pontificate.\nAmong the younger members also are\nCardinal Vivas, prefect of the Congre\ngation of the Religious, that new and\nImportant council created by the Consti\ntution Sapient! Consilio; Cardinal de Lai,\nsecretary of the Conslstorial Congrega\ntion, who has been the Pope\u2019s chief in\nstrument in the reform of the Roman\ncuria; Cardinal Rampolla, secretary of\nthe supreme congregation of the holy of\nfice-first in order of dignity of all Ro\nman congregations; and Cardinal Gas\nparri, prefect of the commission for the\ncodification of canon law; Cardinal Vin\nceizo Vannutelll, prefect of the supreme\ntribunal of the Segnatura, and Cardinal\nCavlochloni, prefect of the congregation\nof studies, will be 74 years of age this\nmonth, but they are still wonderfully ac\ntive and full of energy.\nEven the most cursory observer of the\ntrend of things in the Protestant denomi\nnations of Christendom cannot fall to dis\ncern the evidences of co-operation, fed\neration and unity\u2014all words whose fre\nquent recurrence in the religious periodic\nliterature of the day furnishes the best\nconfirmation possible of the drift of\nthings.\nAddressing the laymen\u2019s federation of\nWashington recently. Dr. Hugh MacCau\nley, secretary of the federal council of\nChurches of Christ in America, gave this\nout of his large experience In the move\nment:\n\"Unification of agencies, reduction of the\ncompetitive system to a minimum, the\nprevention of rivalry and waste\u2014these\nare the watchwords of the federative\ntrend toward consolidation in the realm\nof action, while retaining individualism\nin the realm of thought.\"\nThe general committee of the Methodist\nEpiscopal board has issued an appeal to\nthe various bodies of this denomination.\nIt contained this significant sentence: \"Co\noperation is now the watchword among\nall Protestant denominations. Once they\nwere In hostile array, but now they are\n'one army of the living God.* There la\nan upward trend among the nations char\nacterized by a spirit of toleration and\nreligious liberty heretofore unknown. The\nspirit of co-operation which now perme\nates the Protestant Christian world en\nsures the swifter entering of these forces\nInto the opening doors of a world.\"\nThe tercentenary, or 8f0tb anniversary,\nof the adoption and publication of the King\nJames version of the English Btble Is to\nbe observed by a week of special ser\nvices beginning April 28, 1911. In addi\ntion to the church services It Is proposed\nto have the governors of the state set\naside one day during the week and name\na place where a public meeting In honor\nof the event shall be held. The American\n*dhle society, with headquarters in this\ncity, has also planned to have this his\ntorical event recognized In the schools,\nuniversities, legislatures and courts.\nIt is proposed that the tercentenary be\nbrought to the attention of all clergymen\nand requesting them and all church or\nganizations to plan for* public exercises\nin which the story of the English Bible\nand Its Influence on human life shall be\nset forth. In every large city in the\nUnited States and almost all of the larger\ncities of Europe mass meetings will be\nheld. Missionaries erf the east will ob\nserve the tercentenary. In England the\nendeavor will be made to eclipse the cel\nebration in the United States. There the\ntercentenary will be held during the week\nof March 26. and in Canada, where also\na national .celebration will be held, a week\nin February will be selected as the most\nfitted.\nMr. Chleng Ching-yi, who was elected\nby the World\u2019s Mlsisonary conference In\nEdinburgh to be China\u2019s representative\non the permanent committee, has just\nbeen ordained In Peking to the pastorate\nof the London Missionary society\u2019s\nchurch In the Chinese oapltal. Mr. Chleng\nChing-yl was born 80 years ago in Pe\nking of non-Christian parents, but the\nwhole family becoming Christian, he was\neducated at the Peking and Tlen-tsln\nschools of the London mission, and aft\nerwards for two years in Glasgow. He\nassisted the Rev. George Owen in revising\nthe Mandarin ir\u00bbn nt the Chinese\nBible.\n7\nGEORGE IS FRIENDLY\nWITH WILHELNIINA\n_\nj Rumors of 111 Feeling Are Un\nfounded\nBALFOUR IS TO RETIRE\nLeader of Tory Party \u00a5s Compared to\nBryan Because He Has Met With\nSo Many Defeats\u2014Statue\nDiscovered\nBy PHILLIP EVERETT\nLondon, December 24.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\nannouncement of a coming visit of the\nKing and Queen of Engl&nd to Hollnnd\ncannct very well be interpreted except\nas an effort to put an end to the rumoie\nthat Great Britain feels very much hurt\nbecause of Holland's intention of fortify\ning ber river mouths and particularly of\nbuilding strong fortifications at Flushing.\nLike his late father. King George is very\nmuch interested in the preserve*inn of\nEurolpean peace, and his visit to Queen\nW'ilhelmina's court is to be a visible sign\nthat England is not the slightest af\nfected by French and especially Belgian\nattempts to create ill feeling between\nEngland and Holland by accusing the\nDutch government of having been co\nerced by a personal letter from the\nKaiser Wilhelm to Queen Wilhelmina\nwarning her that If the Dutch coast towns\nwere not fortified against England, Ger\nmany might eventually be compelled to\noccupy them In self defense.\nThat the little country' in Holland will\nbe in great danger in case of war is\nevident, and it is nc moie than natural\nthat she should endeavor to put herself\nin shape to defend the neutrality on\nwhich her national existence depends and\nKing George\u2019s visit will tend to show\nthat the English government is far from\nresenting Holland's plans, which are so\nplainly meant for defense only.\nWith every day the rumor grows I\nstronger, that after the disappointment\nof the recent elections, when the conser\nvative used every dodge and trick to\ncatch votes and failed. Mr. Balfour, who\nis now being compared with William\nJennings Bryan in tactics and lack of\nsuccess, will permanently' retire from the\nleadership, of the tory? party. Three times\nhe has led his party to the polls, and\nthree times they have been defeated.\nNo British statesman, since popular\nrepresentation was established, has such\na record as this,\nMr. Gladstone was once or twice se\nverely beaten, but always at the suc\nceeding election the people again gave\nhim their confidence. He was defeated\nin 1874, but be triumphed in 1880. He was\nbeaten in 1S86. but he was made prime\nminister in 3S92, when the country' next\nhad an opportunity of recording its opin\nion.\nIn 1906 Mr. Balfour was thrust out by\nthe greatest and most overwhelming\nmajority known in British history. In\nJanuary, 1910, after four years of Lib\neral rule, the country again w'ould place\nno confidence in him, and now in Decem\nber, 1910, Tt has been clear that the coun\ntry will not vote to place him in office.\n\u2022The Stars ot Africa,\u201d as the two larg\nest portions of the Cullinan diamond ate\ncalled, will he used for the first time In\nceremonial when King George Is\ncrowned In Westminster abbey next\nJune.\nNo monarch has ever worn two jewels\nso valuable. King Edward decided that\nthe large pear-shaped diamond should be\nplaced In the sceptre and the smaller one\nin the crown. Further, he indicated\nwhere they should be placed. The scep\ntre is that of Charles II, as Is also the\ncrown. King Edward was anxious that\nno part of the sceptre should be removed\nand o-signed to the Jewelers the difficult\ntask of finding space for the great dia\nmond, which Is of the enormous weight\nof ildVdtarats, In the sceptre and retain\ning at the same time the distinctive\nworkmanship and material of the vener\nable symbol of kingly power.\nThis has been successfully done, and\nthe smaller \"Star of Africa\u201d has been\nplaced In the crown Immediately under\nthe tuby of the Black Prince.\nEvidently In the hope of -returning to\nPortugal an absolutely free man against\nwhom the people may find nothing to\nsay. Don Alfonso Henrlques, Duke of\nOporto, who Is at present here In Eng\nland, has Inserted an advertisement in\nthe Lisbon papers, notifying that he de\nsires to pay all his debts In Portugal,\nand has appointed a representative to\ncollect and pay his bills.\nThis notice has caused great surprise,\nDon Alfonso having no fortune, and his\ndebts being estimated at over 1300,000.\nIt la reported that the King of Italy,\nat the request of his sister, Queen Maria\nPI a, recently exiled from Portugal, has\nadvanced money to save the duke from\nbeing prosecuted In the courts for his\ndebts.\nNews comes from Madrid that a new\nmineral has been discovered which pro\nduces aluminum and pure sulphate of\nsoda. As the vein Is a large one It Is\nbelieved that It contains several million\ntons.\nIt is thought that this discovery may\nbring about a revolution In the sulphate\nof soda market, which has up to the\npresent been monopolized by the Ger\nmans. An American firm has already\nmade an offered to purchase 60,000 tone\nof the new mineral annually; but so far\nno decision has been arrived at.\nA discovery of ancient Greek bronce\nstatuettes has been made somewhere In\nEgypt by the peasants, but the sign Is\nknown only to them.\nA splendid figure of Baoehoa, of the\nyouthful Dionysus, It In private hands <n\nCairo, In excellent preservation. One of\nthe hands Is slightly larger than the cor\nrect proportion, but otherwise It Is a fins\nwork. A dealer there has obtained a\nmale bust with floral coronet and sym\nmale bust with floral ooronst and lyra\nor a draped statuette of Aphrodite, of\nwhich the arms from below the elbows\nare unfortunately missing.\nFair Play for the Jew\nFrom Leslie s.\nThe Russian Jew, In order to escape\nthe bitter persecution there visited upon\nhis race, seeks refuge In America. But\nthough we permit no general persecution,\nthe poor Jews In our great cities are\ncompelled daily ,to suffer outrages of one\nsort or another, outrages in no sense\ndeserved, but the result simply of the\nblind reign of prejudice In the minds of\na great many toward this unfortunats\npeople. A movement has been Inaugu\nrated In Chicago to establish a protec\ntion bureau, with a staff of detectives,\nlawyers and others, to prosecute cases\nof persscutlon of Jews. The Immediate\nIncentive, which Is bqt one among many\nsimilar causes constantly arizing, was an\nattack upon a Jewish peddler which end\ned fatally, 'ft Is a common Impression\nthat every Jew possesses wealth, how\never poor he may appear and however\nmeanly he may live. It Is said mat in\nthis case the assailants had received In\nformation that the peddler carried a for\ntune about him, yet upon searching his\nclothes after the murderous attack only\n17 were found. In almost every city one\nmay witness Incidents of petty persecu\ntion of Jews calculated to make the\nblood of any fair-minded person boll, and\nit would serve a good purposg to have\norganisations, like that otarted In Chi\ncago. in every community of the land\nwhere Jews reside In large numbers.\nHOSPITAL SCHOOL\nFORJHE NAVY\nj Young Men Trained for Ser\nvice on War Vessels\nWHILE SHIPS IN ACTION\nOnly Institntlon of Kind In Existence.\nSuccess Has Warranted Establish\nment of Other* In This Coun\ntry and Phllpplnes\nFrom the Washington Star.\nResidents of the southeastern section\nof Washington will, after February* next,\nbe deprived of truly remarkable athletic\nexhibitions. Although a number of the\nparticipants in the exhibitions in question\nare among the best football players in\nthe- country, the spectacles afforded on\nthe spacious grounds of a building at\nNinth street and Pennsylvania avenue.\nSoutheast for the benefit of any passerby\nor spectators are not in the nature of\nthe strenuous winter game, or, indeed,\nany other popularly recognized form of\nsport. The building in the grounds of\nwhich the unique athletic exhibitions are\nto be seen is the Hospital Corps Train\ning school *of the United States navy,\nand the exhibitions themselves are tho\nvarious drills and exercises In which the\nmen of the hospital corps are required to\nbe proficient In order to fit them for\ntheir work on a battleship In action or\nwith tC marine landing party.\nIn the grounds of the hospital corps\nschool is a simple frame structure whioh\nthe passerby on the avenue would prob\nably be puzzled to Identify. This struc\nture, however, plays a prominent part\nin one of the drills, and to see the clean\nlimbed, powerful men springing with the\nagility of panthers from the ground\nthrough a narrow opening in the shed\nlike erection to the roof of the latter,\nand leaping to the ground again, is zo\nsee muscular activity and. concert in ac\ntion at their very best.\nEut this exercise of physical activity\u2019\nis not a spectacular stunt, nor is It gone\nthrough merely in the course of gym\nnasium routine. The distance from tho\nground to the opening through which\nthe men spring is exactly the distance\nfiom the lower deck of a worship to the\nupper and although a ladder hanging to\nthe side of the shed Is employed In the\ndrill, the contingency Is likely to arise,\nin the case of a ship under fire, of the\ncompanion ladder being shot away or\notherwise put out of commission. In\nsuch a case the hospital men must jump\nfrom one deck to the other through the\nhatchway, in order to assist the wounded\nand lower them to the place where their\ninjuries will be cared for. The mere\nphysical activity required in this feat\nmust be seen to' be appreciated.\nNew to Be Started\nThe present class is the last that will\nbe trained at the school, though the\ncourse conducted under the able direc\ntion of Surgeon M. S. Elliott, In com\nmand, will be pursued in the new schools\nto be established In connection with the\nnaval hospitals at New York, Norfolk,\nMarc Island and Canacao, Cavite, Philip\npine Islands, by the direction of Sur\ngeon General Stokes. At present the\nschool In this city Is the only one of Its\nkind in the United States. It is explained\nthat Surgeon General Stokes' intention\nIn extending the hospital training school\nsystem of the navy is to render the\ntraining available to all the men in the\ncorps. \"Under the present plan,\u201d said\nSurgeon Elliott, \"about only 33 per cent\nof the men are able to take the course.\nUnder the system about to be Inaugu\nrated the men, a* soon as they are en\nlisted, will be sent to the training sta\ntions at Newport or San Francisco, where\nthey will remain for four months, un\ndergoing training In naval life. They will\nthen he sent to the different training\nschools at hospitals mentioned for a defi\nnite period, and after becoming proficient\nwill be available for duty on board ship.\"\nIt is not only the open air drills alluded\nto that make the school unique among\nthe institutions of Washington. The vis\nI itor feels, when he has gone over the\ni place, that a glance out of a window'\nshould afford, not the prosaic surroundings\nnf the city, but the vast sparkling or\nmenacing sea, and almost prepares to\nbalance himself against the motion of the\nvessel. In fact, everything is conducted\nas on board a ship. The men sleep in\nhammocks, which are arranged In thor\nough marine fashion, on the top floor of\nthe building. The nautical aspect of the\ndormitory\u2014one Is almost disposed to call\nit a deck\u2014is accentuated by the spick\nand span cleanliness apparent. One\ncould, even in the most hasty and cur\nsory inspection, realize that there is not\na speck of dust to be found on the iron\nuprights or the clean hammocks.\nTraditional Sailor Garb\nOn the subject of cleanliness the naval\nauthorities are, like one of Dickens\u2019\ncharacters in the matter of gravy, ada\nmant. This fact was brought to attention\nby the spectacle of a man in the precincts\nof the school athletically engaged with a\nbrush, soap and water, which he was ex\norcising, In their several capacities, upon\nthe garments peculiar to himself and his\nconfreres. \"It wears out cloth/ \u2018observed\none of the sailors, \u2018but It\u2019s got to be\ndone.\"\nAll the men at the school, by the way,\nare dressed in traditional sailor garb, and\nore thorough jacktars, even to the Inex\nperienced observation of the merest \"land\nlubber.\u201d\nBelow the sleeping deck\u2014or floor\u2014are\nthe wards, the dispensary and the operat\ning room. A very neat young sailor was\nfound presiding over the bottles of drugs\nIn th\u00ab pharmacy, which has the aspect of\na well equipped commercial emporium of\nthe sort, minus the soda water fountain\nand the cigar counter.\n\"The whole object of the school since\nIts beginning,\" said Surgeon Elliott, \"has\nborn to train practical, dependable men.\nThe met!leal corps of the navy could not\nexlrt without the hospital corps. These\nmen under training are. In short, the fu\nture hospital stewards and pharmacists\nof the navy.\"\nThe men are a good class, coming from\ngood families., and harsh discipline is not\nrequired In dealing with them. Some of\nthem are accomplished\u2014one of the pres\nent class is a Harvard graduate; and one,\nan ardent amateur photographer, has\nwritten and Illustrated magazine articles.\nAmericas Styles ta Fashion\nHarriet Quiraby In Leslie's.\nAlthough the term \"American styles\"\nis heard more and more frequently each\nseason, there are few who know that It\nemanates legitimately from an organiza\ntion of American tailors, who devote\ntheir time to designing and producing\nAmerican styles. Just as the French tail\nors and the tailors hof Vienna originate\nnew fashions each year. Those who\nthink enough of the subject to investi\ngate learn that Madame la Mode Paris\nienne, who for so many years held un\ndisputed sway over the civilized coun\ntries on both sides of the Atlantic, has\nlost much of her authority. The well\ndressed English woman, who formerly\nbought all of her clothes in Paris, is now\ndividing her attention between Paris and\nVienna. The American woman is begin\nning to patronize the American tailor.\nMake Way for Prosperity\nIf this country is to have a full return\nof prosperity it must come, as it always\nhas come, through the prosperity of the\nrailroads and the Industrial corporations.\nThe remarkable statement made at the\nrecent annual banquet of the Railway\nBusiness association, In New York, that\n8,000,000 persons are dependent on the\nrailways of this country for support,\ncarries with It Its own Impressive les\nson. Let us call a halt In the attack\non the railway and the Industrial cor^\nporations before It has gone too far, and\nbefore the souphouse takes the place of\nthe factory and the auction thf place of\nthe savin srs h\u00bbAk.\nV\nENSLEY DEPARTMENT 1\nNOTICE\nTo Our Savings Depositors\n\nPlease present your Savings Pass\nBook that the Semi-Annual Inter- l\nest may be credited therein. I\nWe Wish You a Merry Christmas\n\nf\nRAMSAY \u00a3M?COKMACK\n[surplus ^PROFITS. 90000??)\nERSKINE RAMSAY. R. E.CHADWICK.cashier.\nG.B. M9CORMACK. D. P. KNAPP, asst.cashier.\nBOY ACCIDENTALLY\nSHOT BY FRIEND\nLITTLE SON OF J. C. HARTSFIELD\nIS INJURED AT PRATT CITY\u2014ENS\nLEY ELKS TO HAVE CHRISTMAS\nTREE TODAY\nThe 10-year-old son of Detective J. C.\nHartsfleld was accidentally shot and pain\nfully, though not seriously, wounded by\nPerry Vaughn, a playmate.\nThe shooting occurred at the family\nhome In Pratt City, where the two boys\nwere placing with a .41 derringer. Vaughn\nbeing unaware that the weapon was load\ned playfully pointed at Hartsfleld and\npulled the trigger. The bullet took effect\nIn the fleshy part of the arm and for\ntunately the wound Is not serious.\nIt Is considered miraculous that the lit\ntle fellow was not Instantly killed.\n\nElks* Christmas Tree\nThe annual Christmas tree of the Ens\nley lodge of Elks will be given this aft\nernoon at 2:30 o\u2019clock in the lodge hall\non Avenue E. A large number of pres\nents will be given to the poor of the\ncity. The programme is as follows: Open\ning prayer, the Rev. W. T. Walden; open\ning ode, \u201cGreat Ruler of the Universe,\u2019\u2019\nby Elks; solo, John Owen; solo, Mrs.\nMcMellon; piano duet, Mrs. Snow and\nMaster Alvin Keller; solo, Mrs. Hammond\nJones; solo, W. T. Palmer; address, the\nRev. W.: T. Walden; solo, J. L. L*oy;\nclosing ode, Elks.\nBuilding Permit* leaned\nBuilding permits for 25 houses, to be\nbuilt at a cost of 242,000, were Issued yes\nterday by Building Inspector C. S. Mose\nley. Twenty-two of the houses will be\nerected by the Ensley Land company and\nW. R. Stewart will erect three.\nLocal Items\nEvery store In Ensley was packed yes\nterday by a Jolly crowd of happy shop\npers. The day was a reoord one for\nEnsley stores and business was the heav\niest in years.\nSpecial services will be held In all the\nEnsley churches this morning for Christ\nmas Day. A musical programme has been\nprepared by all choirs and those who at\ntend will bo assured not only of a good\nsermon but good music.\nThis morning at 2:30 o'clock the Baraca\nclass of the First Methodist church will\nhold a special meeting to elect officers\nfor the ensuing year. Alt members are\nurged to attend.\nPound Another Job\nFrom the New York Press.\nA. T. Stewart was shown one day by\none of his confidential employes an amus\ning caricature of himself, done In pencil\n\"Good, good!*\u2019 he laughed. 'That Is ex\ncellent. Who did It?\"\n\u201cA young salesman at the linen counter.\nHe scratched It off as you passed the\nother morning. I managed to get It from\nhim and now he's scared stiff for fear\nyou\u2019ll Bee It,\u201d was the laughing reply.\n\"Scared atlff, Is he?\u201d said Mr. Stew\nart, with a twlnkie In his eye. \"Just send\nhim to me, will you?'\nA little later a slim youth entered Mr.\nStewart\u2019s private office and said he un\nderstood he had been aent for. \"Yes,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Stewart gravely, and, holding\nup the sketch, asked: \"Did you do this?\"\nThe lad grew pale and stammered: \"1\n\u2014I beg your pardon, sir\u2014It was only a bit\nof fun\u2014I meant no offense.\"\n\"That's all very well, but you'll have\nto give up your Job here.\u201d\nThe youth humbly protested, when Mr.\nStewart burst out laufehlng and said:\n\"Don't say any more, my boy. I'm only\njoking. Your sketch Is excellent, and, as\nIt would be a sin to keep a man of your\nartistic talent behind a linen counter, I\npropose to supply you with the means to\nstudy art.'*\nMr. Stewart's proposition was gratefully\naccepted, and It was thus that John R.\nRogers, the sculptor, began his artistic\ncarser.\nServed Him Rlgkt\nFrom the Chicago Record-Herald.\n\"The husband of, an actress recently\nwhipped a man In a Chicago restaurant\nfor staring at her.\"\n\"It served him right. A man has no\nbusiness to look at an actress because\nshe has put on clothes that are intended\ntp attract Attention.\"\n\n.'v 1 fc\nBring your Last Winter\u2019s Suits and have them remodeled\ninto this season\u2019s styles\nI. COPLON, The Only Tailor,\n1809 Avenue E. Bell Phone 12\nWe also make your Old Clothes look like New\nSTARTING\nWith the assumption that yon\nhave some friends, isn\u2019t it just\npossible they would like a good\nphotograph of you? Then why\nnot give it to them? You\nwould if you saw how charm\ning we make our\nPHOTOGRAPHS\nStep in our studio aud ex\namine the samples of our work\non view. We think when you\nsee those portraits you\u2019ll want\none of yourself just like them.\nALOIA RICHARD\nPHOTOGRAPHERS\nCorner of 18th St. and Ave. E\nUPSTAIRS\nBell Phone 585\n_\nIDLE HOUR\nTHEATRE\nJ. W. ANDREWS, Manager\nTomorrow, Monday, Dec, 26\nRip Van Winkle\nDon\u2019t miss this great Than\nhouser Masterpiece\n\nAn Awful I.eaaon\nFrom Leslie's.\nHorrible lire tragedies auch as that\nwhich occurred recently In Newark, N.\nJ., Involving the loss of nearly SO lives,\nare constantly occurring In all our great\ncities. While health departments are\nplacing new restrictions on dealers In\nIce, rtiilk, oysters and various other com\nmodities In common use, the building de\npartments In the same cities, with their\neyes wide open, are permitting ftjetraps\nto be erected and others to stand where\nthey have stood as a disgrace to civili\nsation for many years. The muck-raking\npress, sensationalizing every divorce suit\nand every misfortune of the rich, Is blind\nto one of the greatest opportunities that\noffer good service for the protection of\nthe working masses In city -workshops\nand factories against the Ufa flend. Com\nment Is unnecessary!\nNet Progressive\nFrom the Washington Evening Star.\n\u201cI am afraid the revolutionist's Ideas of\nstatesmanship are very crude,\" said one\nSouth American gtatesman.\n\"What's the trouble with him?\u201d rejoined\nthe other.\n\u2022\u2022He lnslete on using a shotgun instead\n\u00abf a repeating rifle.\"\nA- fli! K\nWe wish you a\nMerry Christmas and\na Happy New Year.\nWe will try to have\nbetter pictures in the\nfuture.\nFRANKLIN THEATRE\nChild complimentary ticket\nTuesday, Dec. 27, 1910 i\nGood only on above date\nFRANKLIN\nTHEATRE\nAdmission 5c Ensley, Ala.\n\n\nt\ni\ni 'i\nOpportunity\u2019s Mistake\nFrom the Woman\u2019s Home Companion.\n\u201cThis Is the opportunity of a lifetime,\nmadam,\" declared the smooth-tongued\ncanvasser as he stood at the door.\n\u201cSeems- to me I\u2019ve heard that before,\"\nthought the housewife.\n\u201cOpporunlty knocks at every one\u2019s door\n\u2014but only once,\u201d continued the ealler.\n\"That\u2019s where you\u2019re mistaken, young\nfeller,\" snapped the woman as she i\nreached behind her. Opportunity has j\nknocked at my door eight times this week t\nso far. I\u2019m out |!.10, an\u2019 nothin\u2019 to show\nter It Jest In oase he should knock again\nI be\u2019n savin, this ksttle of hot suds\u2014\"\nBut opportunity departed hurriedly,\n\u2019ijt","height":"28204","width":"19740"}}
